<taxonomicName id="CDAE60D6E4C2E52CB3B465647679B3C0" LSID="458DD2F3-A3EB-CC25-AF1E-607A6859E66E" authority="(DeGeer, 1774)" baseAuthorityName="DeGeer" baseAuthorityYear="1774" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Sericoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sericoda quadripunctata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="732" pageNumber="733" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadripunctata">Sericoda quadripunctata (DeGeer, 1774)</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="749203FA2AC9E6E776D0CDD5E8047D5D" pageId="732" pageNumber="733" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="6FE400E821A9A6F19CE1FD38630422B8" pageId="732" pageNumber="733">
<taxonomicName id="FB7299A04BDF982C0E84E5A9EE7EB1EB" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Carabus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="732" pageNumber="733" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="quadripunctata" subSpecies="4" variety="punctatus">Carabus 4-punctatus</taxonomicName>
DeGeer, 1774: 102. Type locality not stated; &quot;Uppsala, Sweden&quot; selected by Lindroth (1966: 568). Lectotype (♂), designated by Lindroth (1966: 568), in NRSS.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7DAAC960193D124869529724E14526D6" pageId="732" pageNumber="733">
<taxonomicName id="B7E1968B296D1D7188442F91864B58B8" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Carabus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="732" pageNumber="733" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foveolatus">Carabus foveolatus</taxonomicName>
Illiger, 1801: 61. Type locality: Prussia (inferred from title of the paper). Holotype [by monotypy] probably lost. Synonymy established by Gyllenhal (1810: 160).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CAA0410DAD874417AF50208E9C872E57" pageId="732" pageNumber="733">
<taxonomicName id="DB8B036B40214DB9DA6C13D7B60987FC" authorityName="Mannerheim" authorityYear="1853" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Anchomenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="732" pageNumber="733" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="octocolus">Anchomenus octocolus</taxonomicName>
Mannerheim, 1853: 144. Type locality: &quot;ad rivulos fl[umen] Tschunuktnu peninsulae Kenai [Alaska]&quot; (original citation). Holotype [by monotypy] probably in ZMMU. Synonymy established by LeConte (1879b: 57). Note. Regarding the type locality, see 
<normalizedToken id="EDF653A37DEC772C0487383FA73ED495" originalValue="“Note”">&quot;Note&quot;</normalizedToken>
section for 
<taxonomicName id="F899CD763666A0FAE5B3E0A122A09554" authorityName="Mannerheim" authorityYear="1853" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Cryobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="732" pageNumber="733" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subcaudatus">
<emphasis id="0C9B214B37D06386E8D7CBC8785D53AC" italics="true" pageId="732" pageNumber="733">Cryobius subcaudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Mannerheim.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B510E8B2FD687BC1FF48E66927ECE9F3" pageId="732" pageNumber="733">
<taxonomicName id="6E1EB9DF5E81BF91D6765AA61EF231EF" authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1854" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Platynus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="732" pageNumber="733" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stigmosus">Platynus stigmosus</taxonomicName>
LeConte, 1854b: 58. Type locality: &quot;Lake Superior, Maine and New Hampshire&quot; (original citation), restricted to &quot;L[ake] Superior&quot; by Lindroth (1966: 568). Three syntypes in MCZ [# 5785]. Synonymy established with doubt, under the name 
<taxonomicName id="FD7E6801334C2194BB4F13C93C643FE2" baseAuthorityName="Mannerheim" baseAuthorityYear="1853" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Sericoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="732" pageNumber="733" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="octocola">
<emphasis id="0CE4874674F313B8B03DB457C1F09C11" italics="true" pageId="732" pageNumber="733">Sericoda octocola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Mannerheim), by LeConte (1857c: 8), confirmed by Lindroth (1966: 568).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="15B4BBDEB6D97C3A0C225B458E13D369" pageId="732" pageNumber="733">
<taxonomicName id="D1DF7740C09D5AF129EDECB25D55CD7D" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Anchomenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="732" pageNumber="733" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ambiguus">Anchomenus ambiguus</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="96540CD0B5326753F327A64A0CC53914" originalValue="Mäklin">Maeklin</normalizedToken>
, 1855: 36. Type locality: &quot;Ajan [Khabarovsk Kray, Russia]&quot; (original citation). Syntype(s) location unknown (possibly in ZMH). Synonymy established by Jacobson (1907: 330).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="99A9D7BF29D7115B078CE39E2CBB7325" lastPageId="733" lastPageNumber="734" pageId="732" pageNumber="733" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="829F25A12846F1600B3166558A76E3C4" pageId="732" pageNumber="733">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="12CDDD68BCBCEC37585B93EC7A2B350C" lastPageId="733" lastPageNumber="734" pageId="732" pageNumber="733">
This Holarctic species ranges in North America from central Alaska to Newfoundland (Lindroth 1955a: 117), south to eastern North Carolina and west 
<pageBreakToken id="D9C9FC0CB4C2D930E78BA8720C0014EE" pageId="733" pageNumber="734" start="start">ern</pageBreakToken>
Tennessee along the Appalachian Mountains, to northern New Mexico along the Rocky Mountains, and to central Washington [see Liebherr 1991b: Fig. 221]. In the Palaearctic Region, the range of the species extends from Great Britain to the Kamchatka Peninsula, south to the Philippines Islands, the Himalayan Mountains, and Italy in Europe [see Liebherr 1991b: Fig. 222].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="52E72F983E42C20417992BABCE1834FB" pageId="733" pageNumber="734" type="records">
<paragraph id="678F5D4D2A87F5E14CA7620387D8F806" pageId="733" pageNumber="734">Records.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="14D3457FA40EED74E123C29A789577E1" pageId="733" pageNumber="734">
<emphasis id="2BCE0CC348EF3B97254BE8A42591FE91" bold="true" pageId="733" pageNumber="734">CAN</emphasis>
: AB, BC (VCI), LB, MB, NB, NF, NS (CBI), NT, ON, QC, SK, YT 
<emphasis id="E06A192F51D5DF796A1551749D697B58" bold="true" pageId="733" pageNumber="734">USA</emphasis>
: AK, ID, IL, IN, MA, ME, MI, MN, MT, NC, NH, NJ, NM, NY, PA, SD, TN, VT, WA, WI - 
<emphasis id="DE8F01C4ABD64E5D1C8C3BEBF9515159" bold="true" pageId="733" pageNumber="734">Holarctic</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<caption id="A08E1CB47ED2BC3D653AD1B7369DA139" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/30937" pageId="733" pageNumber="734" start="Figure 36" startId="F36">
<paragraph id="E9E34535B1A37449C6F3292ACEC71AD6" pageId="733" pageNumber="734">
<emphasis id="D5BD066DAE49E9CBDAA1DD8308705766" bold="true" pageId="733" pageNumber="734">Figure 36.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="8A309709E0EC7446A719683FEC2ECF01" baseAuthorityName="DeGeer" baseAuthorityYear="1774" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Sericoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="733" pageNumber="734" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadripunctata">
<emphasis id="1CC692D6B30E2F307E96506EEC0A190E" italics="true" pageId="733" pageNumber="734">Sericoda quadripunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(DeGeer). This widely distributed Holarctic species is attracted to fire. The adults are often found in great numbers just after forest fires when the ashes are still hot. This behavior is shared by the other species in the genus and a few other carabids, such as 
<taxonomicName id="771B97CA82B8AE7078E2899F60BAF072" authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1850" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Harpalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="733" pageNumber="734" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laticeps">
<emphasis id="640325C5A8D033DDCF4B9C3548CDDDB2" italics="true" pageId="733" pageNumber="734">Harpalus laticeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="FD7B7C7173B861CD2651AB6FF40B38D5" authorityName="Zetterstedt" authorityYear="1828" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Harpalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="733" pageNumber="734" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevipes">
<emphasis id="0B707BB07D9C722E2FA9DC1AAD36C90E" italics="true" pageId="733" pageNumber="734">Harpalus laevipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The presence of charcoal is probably a stimulus for oviposition. Henri Goulet was unsuccessful in obtaining eggs from 
<taxonomicName id="DF64305CE7D6645EDB8CCB76A1FC07A6" baseAuthorityName="Say" baseAuthorityYear="1823" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Sericoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="733" pageNumber="734" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obsoleta">
<emphasis id="57362D3D700374B6BC285C2D07074D3F" italics="true" pageId="733" pageNumber="734">Sericoda obsoleta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the laboratory until he added charcoal to his rearing containers.
</paragraph>
</caption>
